<subSubSection id="8AF4C87C5FB69332AB3E5655E7575769" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="203680853DF2794B28ECC6A137927D90" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Distribution, habitat and phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2406CF9388D687B52D2304E285BD862F" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicName id="FEC06B02DAB7B268B0EED54DF2BE7BAF" authorityName="C. Toledo" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Connaraceae" genus="Rourea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rourea diamantina" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diamantina">
<emphasis id="521CC270EE6798BC8916F98311BD6CD2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Rourea diamantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from the east side of Chapada Diamantina, a mountain range of about 41,700 km2 and approximately 2,000 m altitude, located in the centre of Bahia (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="966122F4710FEFEDC9C038D14A401DAE" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Geographic distribution of Rourea diamantina (circles) and R. martiana (triangles)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.169.54297.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/484425" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">8</figureCitation>
). Individuals of the new species are mostly shrubs with scandent branches, occurring in seasonal forests of Inselbergs. Specimens have been collected with flowers from September to December and with fruits from November to February and in July.
</paragraph>
<caption id="F1B84362CD45FAA0515E554FE91F7C18" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.169.54297.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/484425" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" start="Figure 8" startId="F8">
