<subSubSection id="C834A138CEDA90204D14A185298ABADF" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="CB68050CF15A4A72A30157392E1AAEC1" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8FBC56B463956E4273B4EC94253074AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
The specific epithet &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="705A3D57B1F0CB738C2C15B6E2C2F74C" authorityName="C. Toledo" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Connaraceae" genus="Rourea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rourea diamantina" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diamantina">Rourea diamantina</taxonomicName>
&quot; refers to Chapada Diamantina (Bahia, Brazil), where the new species is presumed to be endemic. This epithet is a noun in apposition (
<bibRefCitation id="051D85FD6EBFC8AC215CC7CFCECD9060" DOI="https://doi.org/10.12705/Code.2018" author="Turland, NJ" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" refId="B28" refString="Turland, NJ, Wiersema, JH, Barrie, FR, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Kusber, W-H, Li, D-Z, Marhold, K, May, TW, McNeill, J, Monro, AM, Prado, J, Price, MJ, Smith, GF, 2018. International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Shenzhen Code) adopted by the Nineteenth International Botanical Congress Shenzhen, China, July 2017. Regnum Vegetabile 159. Koeltz Botanical Books, Glashuetten. https://doi.org/10.12705/Code.2018" title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Shenzhen Code) adopted by the Nineteenth International Botanical Congress Shenzhen, China, July 2017. Regnum Vegetabile 159. Koeltz Botanical Books, Glashuetten." url="https://doi.org/10.12705/Code.2018" year="2018">Turland et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
, Art. 23.5).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9C0319B1AA4D26A7A6C2AF7D143DA68B" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="recognition and notes">
<paragraph id="4CA7C1374C120ADD22AB314B6D17055E" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Recognition and notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BA29E21DA67DB9468D54A473AFE69CEF" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicName id="990B3814759EA448587809ED25D29C5F" authorityName="C. Toledo" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Connaraceae" genus="Rourea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rourea diamantina" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diamantina">
<emphasis id="A3721FE730F77746DA1CD77B85AE79EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Rourea diamantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recognised by the leaves 5-9(-13)-foliolate, leaflets abaxially hirsute or villous, pedicel with glandular trichomes and sepals with indumentum sericeous internally. An interesting characteristic is the leaves whose leaflets become significantly larger towards the apex. The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="26AD5422745FCB687514CD279B16BE67" family="Connaraceae" genus="R." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="R. martiana" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="martiana">
<emphasis id="979D12EF3EAE8CB5E19CDD3B1EE3CA2D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">R. martiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by the reduced number of leaflets (usually 5-9), which are normally narrowly ovate with obtuse or narrowly-rounded apex, and longer pedicel (5-13 mm long) vs. leaves 9-15-foliolate, leaflets normally oblong or narrowly elliptic with rounded apex and a shorter pedicel (ca. 2 mm long). Additionally, both species are geographically isolated by the Chapada Diamantina (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="62BF10589A32313BDC2C1C351B70CFB0" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Geographic distribution of Rourea diamantina (circles) and R. martiana (triangles)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.169.54297.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/484425" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A5989052561A13A9494469451B0C2F97" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
Some specimens, cited here under 
<taxonomicName id="C2B4F0134CC70103EB7700236DF18D64" authorityName="C. Toledo" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Connaraceae" genus="Rourea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rourea diamantina" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diamantina">
<emphasis id="4DBB5B33AB875A2B7ADF430669042A55" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Rourea diamantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, were previously identified as 
<taxonomicName id="85B6A1389AA52BAFFFBD67DAC187D3ED" family="Connaraceae" genus="R." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="R. martiana" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="martiana">
<emphasis id="3D1F30ED5C33C1F72F243413FB7211BC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">R. martiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="BAE8A4E615EE74E812854E56947976C5" author="Schellenberg, G" editor="Engler, A" journalOrPublisher="W. Engelmann, Leipzig" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" pagination="1 - 326" refId="B25" refString="Schellenberg, G, 1938. Connaraceae. In: Engler, A, Ed., Das Pflanzenreich IV (127) (Heft 103). W. Engelmann, Leipzig: 1 - 326" title="Connaraceae." volumeTitle="Das Pflanzenreich IV (127) (Heft 103)." year="1938">Schellenberg (1938)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="D1F36D9020543D71CEAFEECC4E44E106" author="Forero, E" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" pagination="1 - 119" refId="B10" refString="Forero, E, 1976. A revision of the American species of Rourea subgenus Rourea (Connaraceae). Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 26 (1): 1 - 119" title="A revision of the American species of Rourea subgenus Rourea (Connaraceae)." volume="26" year="1976">Forero (1976</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="511BEE241E6DEB0DF82767E457EAEFB8" author="Forero, E" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" refId="B11" refString="Forero, E, 1983. Connaraceae. Flora Neotropica Monograph 36. New York Botanical Garden Press, New York, 1-208." title="Connaraceae. Flora Neotropica Monograph 36. New York Botanical Garden Press, New York, 1 - 208." year="1983">1983</bibRefCitation>
). After analysing modern collections from Bahia and Minas Gerais, this revision considers that the morphological differences indicated above and their disjunct distribution provide evidence to recognise 
<taxonomicName id="4CA4C2302C5BC22FA2EB776755D4F14F" family="Connaraceae" genus="R." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="R. diamantina" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="diamantina">
<emphasis id="7268F80E9718BF1A63FD930E12B39C14" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">R. diamantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
apart from 
<taxonomicName id="FE23BA7540B052FA6884C28496F7DC22" family="Connaraceae" genus="R." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="R. martiana" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="martiana">
<emphasis id="F73BFA37566DB364AA8EAE5CEE5C641F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">R. martiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For a complete discussion on this subject, see &quot;Recognition and notes&quot; section of 
<taxonomicName id="0E41C097B149D79B6C9F1ACC7BBD6ABA" family="Connaraceae" genus="R." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="R. martiana" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="martiana">
<emphasis id="616799853F763D60FED5EBD1DF8B6A10" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">R. martiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
